'''Michael John "Mike" Kafka''' (born July 25, 1987) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]] who plays [[college football]] for the [[Northwestern Wildcats football|Northwestern Wildcats]].

Kafka attended [[St. Rita of Cascia High School]] in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]] where he played both football and [[baseball]]. Kafka lead St. Rita Cascia to three conference championships. He ended his [[high school football]] career with 1,816 total&nbsp;yards and 16 touchdowns. After his senior season, he moved onto [[Northwestern University]] where he [[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirted]] in 2005. In his first collegiate appearance, Kafka threw a 19&nbsp;yard touchdown pass against [[Miami RedHawks football|Miami]]. Against [[Bowling Green Falcons|Bowling Green]], Kafka suffered a hamstring injury which kept him out until the [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]] game. In 2007, Kafka was the backup to [[C. J. Bacher|C. J. Bach<U+00E9>r]] and played in only two games. Despite being the backup quarterback again in 2008, Kafka threw for 330&nbsp;yards and finished second on the team in rushing&nbsp;yards with 321. Following Bach<U+00E9>r's graduation after the 2008 season, Kafka became the starter for 2009. Before the season he was named to the [[Johnny Unitas Golden Arm Award]] watch list. Against [[Syracuse Orange football|Syracuse]] he set the school record for most pass completions in a row with 16. In the same game, he became the first [[Big Ten Conference]] player to score a passing, receiving and rushing touchdown since [[Zack Mills]] from [[2004 Penn State Nittany Lions football team|Penn State]] in 2004.

==Early years==
Kafka was born on July 25, 1987 to Michael and Sandra Kafka. He attended [[St. Rita of Cascia High School]] in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]] where he played [[High school football|football]] (coached by Todd Kuska) and [[baseball]]. He was the team captain for both teams. In football, he led the Mustangs to three conference championships and had a career record of 35<U+2013>8. As a senior in 2004, Kafka threw 129 passes and completed 75 of them. Against [[Mt. Carmel High School]], he ran for 164&nbsp;yards and passed for 126&nbsp;yards. Kafka passed for 1,004&nbsp;yards and 10 [[touchdown]]s in 2004. He ran for 806&nbsp;yards with a 5.6&nbsp;yards per [[Carry (American football)|carry]] average, and five touchdowns on 144 carries. His career stats at St. Rita was 1,816 total offensive&nbsp;yards and 16 touchdowns.<ref name=NU/>

He made the school's Silver Honor Roll all four years of high school and was an Academic All-State. He was an All-area selection by ''Tom Lemming's Prep Football Report'' and was an honorable mention all-state selection. ''SuperPrep'' named him All-Midwest Region and Rivals.com placed him on the Top 25 dual-threat quarterbacks list. ''SuperPrep'' ranked him 25th among players from Illinois at all positions and 50th nationally among quarterbacks. He was ranked 20th in Illinois by Rivals.com and 25th nationally among dual-threat quarterbacks. Kafka was named Team Offensive MVP and Catholic Metro Blue Offensive MVP. He was an honorable mention all-area honree by ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' and ''[[Daily Southtown]]''.<ref name=NU/>

==College career==
===2005 season===
During the 2005 season, his first year, Kafka [[redshirted]] in order for him to learn [[2005 Northwestern Wildcats football team|Northwestern Wildcats']] offensive system.<ref name="NU">{{cite web|url=http://nusports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/kafka_mike00.html |title=#13 Mike Kafka|work=[[Northwestern University]]|accessdate=2009-09-28}}</ref>

===2006 season===
In his Northwestern career debut on September 1 versus [[2006 Miami RedHawks football team|Miami University]], Kafka threw for 106&nbsp;yards and one [[touchdown]] on 13 completions out of 17 attempts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=262430193|title=Northwestern 21, Miami (OH) 3|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-10-02}}</ref> His first touchdown was a 19-yard pass to [[running back]] [[Tyrell Sutton]]. He led all players with 89&nbsp;yards rushing on 17 [[Rush (American football)|rushing]] attempts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://northwestern.scout.com/2/563380.html|title=Cats, Fitz give Red Hawks Fits|last=Lamberton|first=Roy|work=[[Scout.com]]|date=2009-09-01|accessdate=2009-09-28}}</ref> His [[passer rating]] for that game was 148.26 as Northwestern went on to win 21<U+2013>3. <ref name="NU" /><ref name="Herald">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/story/?id=326662&src=289 |title=Once clueless, NU's Kafka looking forward to Miami |publisher=''[[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights)|Daily Herald]]'' |date=October 6, 2009 |accessdate=2009-10-06}}</ref>

Against [[New Hampshire Wildcats|New Hampshire]] on September 9, Kafka went 19<U+2013>32 and threw for 173&nbsp;yards along with one [[Interception (American football)|interception]] and a fumble.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=262520077|title=Northwestern stunned in home opener by I-AA New Hampshire|date=September 9, 2006|work=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-10-02}}</ref> He rushed for 42&nbsp;yards. The Wildcats ended up losing the game, 34<U+2013>17.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=262520077|title=New Hampshire 34, Northwestern 17|date=September 9, 2006|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-10-02}}</ref>

He played the first half of the game against [[Eastern Michigan Eagles football|Eastern Michigan]] and rushed for 33&nbsp;yards with a 6.6&nbsp;yards per run average, along with his first career rushing touchdown, a 6-yard run. He passed for 76&nbsp;yards and completed 10 out of 18 passes with an interception.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.covers.com/articles/articles.aspx?theArt=91211&tid=30&t=0|title=Game of the day: Northwestern at Nevada|last=Macrae|first=Darcy|date=September 21, 2006|work=Covers.com|accessdate=2009-10-02}}</ref>

Days before Northwestern faced [[Nevada Wolf Pack football|Nevada]], coach [[Pat Fitzgerald]] confirmed that Kafka would remain the starter despite his prior performanaces.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://goliath.ecnext.com/coms2/gi_0199-5795705/NU-still-adjusting-on-offense.html|title=NU still adjusting on offense|last=Rittenberg|first=Adam|date=September 19, 2006|work=Daily Herald|accessdate=2009-10-02}}</ref> In the game, Kafka ran for a career-high 111&nbsp;yards, which included a 13-yard touchdown rush, and averaged 9.2&nbsp;yards per rush. He passed for 122&nbsp;yards, completing 9 out of 21 passes and three interceptions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=262652440|title=Northwestern 21, Nevada 31|date=September 22, 2006|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-10-02}}</ref> His 111&nbsp;yards rushing were the most by a Northwestern quarterback since [[Zak Kustok]] ran for 111&nbsp;yards in a November 21, 2001 game versus [[Bowling Green Falcons football|Bowling Green]]. Kafka suffered a hamstring injury during the game, which kept him out of the next three games of the season.<ref name="NU" />

Kafka made his first appearance since suffering a hamstring injury against [[2006 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]], in which he passed for 17&nbsp;yards and completed 4 out of 8 passes. He averaged <U+2212>4.0&nbsp;yards per carry.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=263150077|title=Ohio State 54, Northwestern 10|date=November 11, 2006|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-10-02}}</ref>

===2007 season===
In 2007, Kafka was a backup and only played in two games, where he passed for 11&nbsp;yards on two completions and rushed for eight&nbsp;yards.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=272440077|title=Northeastern 0, Northwestern 27|date=September 1, 2007|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-10-03}}</ref><ref name=NU/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=272650194|title=Northwestern 7, Ohio State 58|date=September 22, 2007|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-10-03}}</ref>

===2008 season===
Kafka entered the [[2008 Northwestern Wildcats football team|2008 season]] as a backup quarterback behind C. J. Bach<U+00E9>r.<ref name=NU/> Against [[2008 Syracuse Orange football team|Syracuse]], Kafka entered the game in the fourth quarter and rushed twice for 18&nbsp;yards, which included an 11-yard run.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=282430077|title=Syracuse 10, Northwestern 30|date=August 30, 2008|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-10-03}}</ref> Against [[Southern Illinois Salukis#Football|Southern Illinois]], he threw two passes and completed one for one yard and rushed for three&nbsp;yards.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=282570077|title=Southern Illinois 7, Northwestern 33|date=September 13, 2008|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-10-03}}</ref> He played in the final series at [[2008 Indiana Hoosiers football team|Indiana]] and completed a pass, which went for nine&nbsp;yards.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=282990084|title=Northwestern 19, Indiana 21|date=October 25, 2008|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-10-03}}</ref>

Starting in place of the injured Bach<U+00E9>r for the game<ref name="Record">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=283060135|title=Northwestern upsets Minnesota with late pick for touchdown|date=November 1, 2008|work=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-10-03}}</ref> against [[2008 Minnesota Golden Gophers football team|Minnesota]], Kafka ran for 217&nbsp;yards on 27 attempts, which included a 53-yard run, and passed for 143&nbsp;yards and two touchdowns on 12 completions out of 16 throws.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=283060135|title=Northwestern 24, Minnesota 17|date=November 1, 2008|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-10-03}}</ref> His 217 rushing&nbsp;yards set a school and [[Big Ten Conference]] record for quarterback rushing&nbsp;yards in a game.<ref name="Record" /> He began the game by completing his first eight throws, which included a 36-yard touchdown pass to [[Jeremy Ebert]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/playbyplay?gameId=283060135&period=1|title=1st Qtr Play-by-Play|date=November 1, 2008|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-10-03}}</ref> He was named the team's offensive player of the week after that game, along with being named the Big Ten Co-Offensive Player of the Week. Kafka earned an ESPN College Gameday Helmet Sticker and was named an AT&T All-America Plauer of the Week candidate.<ref name=NU/>

The next week, Kafka started in his second straight game against [[2008 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]], and passed for 177&nbsp;yards while completing 18 out of 27 throws. He ran for 83&nbsp;yards and a touchdown on 29 attempts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=283130077|title=Ohio State 45, Northwestern 10|date=November 8, 2008|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-10-03}}</ref> He ran for 300&nbsp;yards in his two starts against Ohio State, which is the most by a Northwestern quarterback in successive contests. He was named the team's offensive big playmaker for the game.<ref name=NU/>

Against [[2008 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]], he entered the game in Northwestern's second series on offense and rushed for 20&nbsp;yards on three carries<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=283200130|title=Northwestern 21, Michigan 14|date=November 15, 2008|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-10-03}}</ref> before he was forced to leave the game after suffering a concussion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=3704412|title=Northwestern's Kafka leaves game vs. Michigan with concussion|date=November 15, 2008|work=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-10-03}}</ref> He ran for one&nbsp;yard on three carries against [[2008 Illinois Fighting Illini football team|Illinois]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=283270077|title=Illinois 10, Northwestern 27|date=November 22, 2008|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-10-03}}</ref>

Kafka passed for 330&nbsp;yards during the season along with two touchdowns on 32 completions and 46 total attempts. He finished second on the team in rushing with 321&nbsp;yards.<ref name=NU/>

===2009 season===
Kafka entered his senior season as [[2009 Northwestern Wildcats football team|Northwestern's]] starting quarterback after C. J. Bach<U+00E9>r graduated. He has been named to the [[Johnny Unitas Golden Arm Award]] watch list, along with 19 other players nationally, with two others in the Big Ten Conference.<ref name="NU" />

At home against [[Towson Tigers|Towson]] on September 5 to start the 2009 season, Kafka threw for 192&nbsp;yards on 15 completions of 20 attempts. He ran for six&nbsp;yards on six carries.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=292480077|title=Towson 14, Northwestern 47|date=September 5, 2009|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2009-10-03}}</ref> Against [[2009 Eastern Michigan Eagles football team|Eastern Michigan]] at home on September 12, he threw for 158&nbsp;yards and one interception on 14 completions out of 24 attempts. He ran for 21&nbsp;yards on five runs.<ref name="Stats">{{cite web|url=http://collegefootball.rivals.com/cviewplayer.asp?Player=52270|title=Mike Kafka|work=[[Rivals.com]]|accessdate=2009-09-28}}</ref> During the [[2009 Syracuse Orange football team|Syracuse]] game, Kafka set a school record for consecutive completions in a game with 16, breaking the 47-year-old record set by Tom Myers in 1962. He set a career-high in passing&nbsp;yards in a game by passing for 390&nbsp;yards. His previous career-high was 192&nbsp;yards in a game against Towson in the 2009 season opener. Kafka also ran for a three-yard touchdown and threw three touchdown passes along with an interception. He caught a receiving touchdown when he tossed a lateral to [[Andrew Brewer]] who threw it back to Kafka for a 24-yard touchdown. Kafka became the first Big Ten Conference player to score at least one passing, receiving and rushing touchdown in a game since [[Zack Mills]] from [[2004 Penn State Nittany Lions football team|Penn State]] accomplished it on September 4, 2004 against [[Akron Zips football|Akron]]. Kafka finished the game with 35 completions on 42 attempts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nusports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/091909aaa.html|title=Mike Kafka Sets School Records in 37<U+2013>34 Defeat at Syracuse|work=Northwestern University|accessdate=2009-09-28}}</ref> Kafka passed for 309&nbsp;yards, two touchdowns and an interception against [[2009 Minnesota Golden Gophers football team|Minnesota]]. He took four [[Quarterback sack|sacks]] and during a desperation drive to win the game, fumbled the football, which helped end the game.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/chi-27-northwestern-football-sep27,0,3555456.story|title=Northwestern blows lead in 4th quarter, loses 35<U+2013>24 to Minnesota|date=September 27, 2009|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=2009-09-28}}</ref><ref name="Kafka">{{cite news|url=http://www.suntimes.com/sports/colleges/1800376,CST-SPT-nu01.article|title=Running magic so far MIA for Wildcats QB Kafka|date=October 1, 2009|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|accessdate=2009-10-01}}</ref> In the [[2009 Purdue Boilermakers football team|Purdue]] game, Kafka went 28-of-44 and threw for 224&nbsp;yards. He rushed for a season-high 39&nbsp;yards on 18 carries and ran for the game-winning two-yard touchdown. After leading after the touchdown 25<U+2013>21, Kafka threw a successful two-point conversion pass to Drake Dunsmore to increase the lead by six to win the game after Purdue failed to score on the final drive of the game.<ref>{{cite web |title=Northwestern 27, Purdue 21 |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=292762509&confId=5 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=October 3, 2009 |accessdate=2009-10-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Northwestern 2-minute drill |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/chi-04-drill-northwestern-oct04,0,7899139.story |publisher=''Chicago Tribune'' |date=October 4, 2009 |accessdate=2009-10-05}}</ref> Kafka went 15 completions of 31 attempts for 191&nbsp;yards and one interception to lead Northwestern to a 16<U+2013>6 win over [[2009 Miami RedHawks football team|Miami (OH)]]. He was the leading rusher for Northwestern, rushing for 53&nbsp;yards on 15 carries and two touchdowns.<ref>{{cite web |title=Miami (OH) 6, Northwestern 16 |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=292830077 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=October 10, 2009 |accessdate=2009-10-10}}</ref> In the 24<U+2013>14 loss at [[2009 Michigan State Spartans football team|Michigan State]] on October 17, Kafka went 34-for-47 and threw for 291&nbsp;yards and two touchdowns. He was the leading rusher for the second straight week for Northwestern, rushing for 42&nbsp;yards on 18 carries.<ref>{{cite web |title=Northwestern 14, Michigan State 24 |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=292900127 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=October 17, 2009 |accessdate=2009-10-21}}</ref> In a come-from-behind win against [[2009 Indiana Hoosiers football team|Indiana]], the Wildcats trailed 28<U+2013>3 during the second quarter before Kafka ran for a one-yard touchdown and later passed for two touchdowns to lead Northwestern to a 29<U+2013>28 win. The Wildcats overcame a 25-point deficit, which was the biggest comeback in school history.<ref name="BigTen">{{cite web |title=Northwestern game notes |url=http://www.bigtennetwork.com/news/article.asp?story_id=3372830&list_id=46 |publisher=Big Ten Network |date=October 24, 2009 |accessdate=2009-10-25}}</ref> He went 26-of-46 and passed for 312&nbsp;yards, along with two touchdowns and a career-tying three interceptions. He rushed for 65&nbsp;yards on 17 carries and one touchdown.<ref>{{cite web |title=Indiana 28, Northwestern 29 |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=292970077&confId=5 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=October 24, 2009 |accessdate=2009-10-24}}</ref> Kafka totaled 377&nbsp;yards of total offense, which is second-best in his career.<ref name="BigTen"/> Against 12th ranked [[2009 Penn State Nittany Lions football team|Penn State]], Kafka went 14-for-18 and passed for 128&nbsp;yards, along with rushing for 42&nbsp;yards on eight carries and a touchdown before leaving the game with a leg injury during the second quarter.<ref>{{cite web |title=(12) Penn State 34, Northwestern 13 |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=293040077 |publisher=''ESPN.com'' |date=October 31, 2009 |accessdate=2009-11-08}}</ref> He was replaced by [[Dan Persa]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Persa replaces injured Kafka at QB |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/chicago/ncf/news/story?id=4611809 |publisher=''ESPN.com'' |date=October 31, 2009 |accessdate=2009-11-08}}</ref> Kafka shared time at quarterback with Persa due to his strained hamstring on November 7 against the 4th-ranked, and previously undefeated, [[2009 Iowa Hawkeyes football team|Iowa Hawkeyes]]. Northwestern coming into the game was a 16-point underdog, but still beat Iowa 17<U+2013>10 in Northwestern<U+2019>s first win over a nationally-ranked top-ten team since they won against [[2004 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |author=Morrissey, Rick |title=Northwestern in state of euphoria, Notre Dame in state of dismay |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/chi-08-morrissey-notre-dame-nu-nov08,0,5729585.story |publisher=''Chicago Tribune'' |date=November 8, 2009 |accessdate=2009-11-13}}</ref> Persa had to leave the game early to receive [[X-rays]] for a hand injury, which forced Kafka to play more than original planned.<ref>{{cite web |title=Northwestern topples No. 8 Iowa to gain an opportunity at a quality bowl |url=http://www.americanchronicle.com/articles/yb/137468428 |publisher=''Chicago Tribune'' |accessdate=2009-11-13}}</ref> He finished as Northwestern<U+2019>s leading passer with 72&nbsp;yards on ten completions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Northwestern 17, (4) Iowa 10 |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=293112294 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=November 7, 2009 |accessdate=2009-11-13}}</ref> Against [[2009 Illinois Fighting Illini football team|Illinois]] on November 14, Kafka threw for 305&nbsp;yards and went 23-of-37, along with a 28-yard touchdown pass to [[wide receiver]] [[Zeke Markshausen]]. He rushed seven times for 12&nbsp;yards and a one-yard touchdown to beat the Fighting Illini 21<U+2013>16. Kafka threw for 300 or more yards for the fourth time this season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Northwestern 21, Illinois 16 |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=293180356&confId=5 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=November 14, 2009 |accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref>

As of week 8, Kafka leads the Big Ten Conference in passing yards and total offense with 258.4 passing yards per game and 284.1 total offensive yards per game.<ref>{{cite web |author=Wogenrich, Mark |title=Liberty High grad Persa contributing at Northwestern |url=http://www.mcall.com/sports/college/all-s-psu.7070378oct30,0,6528323.story |publisher=''[[The Morning Call]]'' |date=October 30, 2009 |accessdate=2009-11-12}}</ref> As of week 7, he is second in the Big Ten in rushing touchdowns with four.<ref>{{cite web |author=Rittenberg, Adam |title=Midseason review: Northwestern |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/bigten/post/_/id/5625/midseason-review-northwestern |publisher=ESPN.com |date=October 20, 2009 |accessdate=2009-10-24}}</ref> As of week 10, his 66.2 completion percentage for 2009 ranks first in the Big Ten and, as of week 7, seventh nationally.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/chi-30-greenstein-inside-big-ten-sep30,0,3101207.story|title=Illinois coach OK with last Ohio State touchdown|date=September 30, 2009|work=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=2009-09-29}}</ref><ref name="Completions">{{cite web |author=O'Donnell, Jim |title=NU taking high road quite often |url=http://www.southtownstar.com/sports/1883408,111509sptnu1star.article |publisher=''[[SouthtownStar]]'' |date=November 14, 2009 |accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref> As of week 7, his 255 pass attempts this season ranks seventh among all quarterbacks nationally.<ref>{{cite web |author=Decker, John |title=N'WESTERN: Five Days and Counting |url=http://indiana.scout.com/2/910685.html# |publisher=Scout.com |date=Oct. 19, 2009 |accessdate=2009-10-24}}</ref> As of week 8, he leads the Big Ten in completions per game with 22.3.<ref name="Completions"/> Kafka ranks 14th on Northwestern's single-season passing yardage list with 2,067&nbsp;yards.<ref name="BigTen"/> As of week 8, Kafka leads Northwestern in rushing with 248&nbsp;yards, 27.6&nbsp;yards per game and six touchdowns.<ref name="Rushing">{{cite web |author=Greenstein, Teddy |title=Northwestern's Mike Kafka off injury report |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/chi-06-northwestern-football-nov06,0,7557758.story |publisher=''Chicago Tribune'' |date=November 6, 2009 |accessdate=2009-11-13}}</ref>

